  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite being published in 2020 by Leuven University Press, \"Migration at Work\" has not achieved citation or online engagement metrics indicative of broad scholarly or societal impact. However, it shows a strong commercial linkage through platforms like Amazon and Goodreads, suggesting potential interest among readers and practitioners in the field of migration studies.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book \"Migration at Work,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2020, delves into the complexities of migration in the labor market, yet to date, it has not garnered academic citations or higher visibility on social platforms. Despite these metrics suggesting limited engagement, it is important to note that the work is commercially linked, with notable presence on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, which hints at interest in its subject matter outside of strict academic circles.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although citation counts stand at zero, indicating that the academic community has not yet widely adopted this work, the inferred role of policy relevance remains noteworthy, particularly concerning sustainability issues. The work\u2019s alignment with one of the Sustainable Development Goals suggests a potential application in policy discussions, which could become more pronounced as global migration debates continue to evolve.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of community discourse on prominent social platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, and Bluesky indicates that the book has not yet sparked public conversation or captured the attention of non-academic audiences. This may reflect broader challenges within the migration studies domain, where engaging narratives are necessary to bridge academic insights with public understanding and discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In a landscape where many scholarly works strive for immediate societal impact, \"Migration at Work\" demonstrates the challenges of transitioning academic research into the public domain. The lack of engagement metrics serves as a reminder of the importance of strategic dissemination and the need for continued efforts to relate academic output to pressing societal issues, particularly in the area of migration.</p>",
